rom police archives to personal papers and interviews, provides a convincing explanation of this quixotic figure—a man who founded French fascism only to turn to the radical left and eventually die as a resister in Bergen-Belsen.At a time when radical socialism is in decline and neofascist movements are gaining renewed support—in France and elsewhere—this original interpretation of Georges Valois's life and thought could not be more timely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPoliticianszFrancevBiography. 0aPoliticians. 0aRight and left (Political science)zFrancevBiography. 0aRight and left (Political science). 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aanarchism.  aanarchy.  aautobiography.  aeconomic organizer.  afamous publisher.  afamous writer.  afrench facism.  afrench republic.  afrench revolution.  alibertarian socialism.  amemoir biography.  aneofascist movement.  apersonal papers.  apolice archives.  apolitical organizer.  aradical political movements.  aradical socialism.  arenewed support.  asocialism and communism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007678540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520912090?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912090/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY